Place a #pot{} over medium-high heat with @water{300%ml}, @ground turmeric{1%sachet} and @vegetable stock{1%sachet}.

Bring to the boil then add the @rice{150%g}.

Once boiling, lower the heat to medium and cover with the #lid{}.

Cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pot from the heat.

Keep covered for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, drain the @tofu{180%g} and chop into 2cm cubes. Pat dry with #kitchen paper{}.

Toss with half the @North Indian Style Spice Mix{2%sachets}, a drizzle of @oil{to taste}, ½ tsp @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Place a pan over high heat with a good glug of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the tofu until slightly crispy, ~{6-8%minutes}. Shift frequently to ensure it doesn't burn. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Once cooked, remove from the pan and set aside.

Meanwhile, halve, peel and chop the @onion{2}(peeled and chopped into small pieces).

Return the pan to medium-high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Fry the onion until softened, ~{3-4%minutes}. Season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

Blend the @cashews{20%g} and @creme fraiche{220%g} together with a #blender{}.

Add the remaining North Indian spice to the pan. Cook for ~{1%minute} then add tofu, cashew cream, @passata{1%pack}, @sugar{1/2%tsp} and a knob of @butter{to taste}. Cook for ~{5-7%minutes}.

> TIP: No blender? No problem! Finely chop the cashews instead!

Taste the curry and season with @salt{to taste}, @pepper{to taste} and @sugar{to taste}. Loosen with a splash of @water{to taste} if you feel it's too thick.

Roughly chop the @coriander{5%g}(roughly chopped, stalks and all).

Fluff up the pilau rice with a #fork{} and serve alongside the creamy curry.

Finish with a sprinkling of coriander.